      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Are fiber gummies as effective as fiber powder for kids?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Fiber gummies typically deliver 3 to 5 grams of fiber per serving compared to 5 to 7 grams in powder supplements. While the absolute dose is lower, gummies offer significantly better compliance in children — a child who actually takes a gummy every day receives more total fiber than one who resists or refuses a powder supplement mixed into drinks. The fiber types used in gummies (inulin, wheat dextrin) are equally effective gram-for-gram as those in powders. For severe constipation, powders may be more appropriate due to higher dosing flexibility.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'At what age can kids start taking fiber gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Most fiber gummy manufacturers recommend their products for children ages 4 and older due to choking hazard concerns with gummy supplements in younger children. Some brands offer fiber gummies specifically formulated for ages 2 and up with softer textures and smaller sizes. Always supervise young children while taking gummy supplements. For toddlers under 2, consult your pediatrician before supplementing fiber, as dietary adjustments (more fruits, vegetables, and whole grains) are the preferred first approach for this age group.' },
