    <h2 id="why-kids-need-fiber">Why Most Kids Are Not Getting Enough Fiber</h2>

    <p>The fiber gap in American children's diets is one of the most overlooked nutritional deficiencies in pediatric health. According to the USDA, only 5% of children ages 4 to 18 meet the recommended daily fiber intake established by the Institute of Medicine. The average American child consumes approximately 13 grams of fiber per day — roughly half the recommended amount for their age group. This chronic fiber deficit has measurable consequences for digestive health, immune function, and long-term metabolic development.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">5%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">Of American children meet the recommended daily fiber intake. The average child consumes <strong>approximately 13 grams per day — half the recommended amount</strong>. Fiber supplementation can bridge this critical nutritional gap.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Fiber is not just about regularity. Prebiotic fibers like inulin and fructooligosaccharides (FOS) serve as fuel for beneficial gut bacteria — particularly Bifidobacterium and Lactobacillus species — that play essential roles in immune development, nutrient absorption, and even mood regulation through the gut-brain axis. A 2019 study in the <em>Journal of Pediatric Gastroenterology and Nutrition</em> found that children who consumed adequate prebiotic fiber had significantly more diverse gut microbiomes and fewer episodes of upper respiratory infections compared to fiber-deficient children.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Digestive regularity</strong>
        <p>Soluble fiber absorbs water to form a gel that softens stool and promotes regular bowel movements. Constipation affects up to 30% of children and is the most common reason for pediatric GI referrals.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Prebiotic gut health</strong>
        <p>Chicory root inulin increases bifidobacteria populations within 2 weeks in pediatric studies. A diverse gut microbiome supports immune development, nutrient absorption, and metabolic health throughout childhood.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Immune system support</strong>
        <p>70% of the immune system resides in the gut. Prebiotic fiber fuels beneficial bacteria that produce short-chain fatty acids (SCFAs), which strengthen the intestinal barrier and modulate immune responses.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Blood sugar regulation</strong>
        <p>Soluble fiber slows glucose absorption after meals, preventing the blood sugar spikes that contribute to energy crashes, irritability, and difficulty concentrating in school-age children.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

