    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Fiber Gummies for Kids</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much fiber do kids need daily?</summary>
      <p>The AAP recommends the "age plus 5" rule — a child's age plus 5 grams. A 6-year-old needs about 11 grams daily. The Institute of Medicine recommends 19g for ages 1-3, 25g for ages 4-8, and 26-31g for ages 9-13. Most American children consume fewer than 15 grams — well below recommendations.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What type of fiber is best for kids?</summary>
      <p>Soluble prebiotic fibers like chicory root inulin, partially hydrolyzed guar gum, and wheat dextrin are best-tolerated in children's gummies. These fibers dissolve in water, form a gel in the digestive tract, and fuel beneficial gut bacteria. Chicory root inulin increases bifidobacteria populations within 2 weeks in pediatric studies.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can fiber gummies cause stomach problems in kids?</summary>
      <p>Introducing fiber too quickly can cause temporary gas, bloating, or loose stools. Start with half the recommended serving for the first week. Ensure adequate water intake. If symptoms persist, try a different fiber type — wheat dextrin (Benefiber) or acacia fiber (Garden of Life) tend to cause fewer GI symptoms than inulin.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are fiber gummies as effective as fiber powder?</summary>
      <p>Gummies deliver 3-5g per serving versus 5-7g in powders. However, gummies offer significantly better compliance in children. A child who takes a gummy daily receives more total fiber than one who resists powder. For severe constipation, powders may be better due to higher dosing flexibility.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>At what age can kids start taking fiber gummies?</summary>
      <p>Most brands recommend age 4+ due to choking hazards. L'il Critters is suitable from age 2+ with supervision. For toddlers under 2, consult your pediatrician — dietary adjustments are the preferred first approach.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much sugar is in kids fiber gummies?</summary>
      <p>Most contain 2-4g sugar per serving. Sugar-free options using sugar alcohols are available but may cause GI discomfort. The fiber in gummies offsets some glycemic impact by slowing sugar absorption. Vitafusion Fiber Well Kids is our top sugar-free recommendation.</p>
    </details>

